[b]Reversal Type Classifier [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
An ex-post diagnostic indicator that classifies every confirmed pivot reversal into one of four outcome types — painted at the pivot bar once the evaluation window has closed. It is intentionally not a real-time entry signal; it is a research and gate-design tool for understanding what pivot reversals actually produce in a given market and timeframe.

[b]Reversal Types[/b]
[list]
[*][b]A — Snapback:[/b] Price hits the snap target in R within the configured max bars, before stopping out. Fast, decisive reversal.
[*][b]B — Grind:[/b] Price reaches the grind target before fail, or achieves meaningful follow-through without stopping out. Slow, sustained reversal.
[*][b]C — Fake/Pullback:[/b] Fail threshold hit first, or follow-through is below the minimum. The setup looked good but reversed against the pivot.
[*][b]D — Chop/Unclear:[/b] Sufficient pivot impulse but no decisive outcome in either direction within the window.
[/list]

[b]Context per pivot (tooltip)[/b]
[list]
[*]WaveTrend value at the pivot bar
[*]Bullish/bearish divergence vs. the prior same-direction pivot
[*]Oversold/overbought extreme flag
[*]Trend-against flag (EMA direction + ADX strength)
[*]Chop flag (ADX below threshold)
[*]MFE and MAE in R units
[*]ATR rank at the pivot bar
[*]Composite quality score (0–100)
[/list]

[b]Inputs[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Pivot / Evaluation:[/b] Pivot confirmation length, evaluation window, minimum impulse filter
[*][b]WaveTrend:[/b] Channel, average, and signal lengths; OS/OB levels
[*][b]Outcome in R:[/b] Snap target, grind target, fail threshold, minimum follow-through, snap bar limit
[*][b]Context / Quality:[/b] EMA trend length, ADX settings, ATR rank lookback
[*][b]Display:[/b] Toggle each type, background zones, statistics table
[/list]

[b]Typical use[/b]
[list]
[*]Run on a symbol/timeframe to see the historical distribution of reversal outcomes
[*]Use tooltip context (divergence, WT extreme, trend flags) to identify which conditions consistently produce A/B vs. C/D outcomes
[*]Feed findings into gate design for entry strategies
[/list]

